Synthetic spectra of rotating stars.

Authors: 
	Timothy D. Brandt
	Mikhail Lipatov

Model: 
	Roche model of mass distribution, 
	non-differential rotation,
	energy flux collinear with effective gravity.

Input:	
	Star's 
		mass, 
		luminosity,
		equatorial radius,
		rotation speed,
		inclination;
	Specific intensity as a function of 
		wavelength, 
		surface inclination, 
		effective temperature, 
		effective gravity,
		metallicity.

Methods:
	Roche model surface via the cubic formula,
	Temperature and gravity via Newton's method,
	Intensity via 
		piecewize polynomial fits w.r.t. surface inclination,
		bilinear interpolation w.r.t temperature and gravity;
	1D integration via a 4th-order scheme.

Installation:
	pip install .

Executables:
	calc_limbdark.py computes fits w.r.t surface inclination
	calc_star.py performs inclination-independent computations
	calc_spectra.py computes spectra for multiple inclinations
	plot_spectrum.py plots a spectrum at a single inclination 
	python <command.py> -h provides usage instructions

References: 
	Espinosa Lara F & Rieutord M (2011), A&A, 533, A43 [EL]
	Castelli F & Kurucz RL (2004), arXiv:astro-ph/0405087 [Kurucz]
	http://mathworld.wolfram.com/CubicFormula.html
	Wikipedia:Bilinear interpolation:Algorithm
	Wikipedia:Newton's method
	Press WH et al, Numerical Recipes, 3rd ed. (2007)
